what does this command do: ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com
The command is used to establish a secure connection between two servers using the SSH protocol. The -i option specifies the path to the UserKey.pem file, which is used as a key for authentication. The -C flag tells the server that it should run in interactive mode, allowing the user to input commands directly. The -L flag specifies the local port (25900) and the remote host (ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com), indicating that traffic should be forwarded from the local machine to the remote server on port 5900. Finally, the user@ option specifies the username for authentication purposes.
